  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a very strong and globally recognized consensus that money laundering is against the law.\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **International Laws and Treaties:** Numerous international treaties and conventions, such as the United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (Vienna Convention), the United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (Palermo Convention), and the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations, explicitly criminalize money laundering. These treaties have been ratified by a vast majority of countries.\n\n*   **National Laws:** Virtually every country has enacted laws to combat money laundering. These laws vary in detail, but they all share the common goal of prohibiting the concealment of the origins of illegally obtained money. Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including imprisonment, hefty fines, and asset forfeiture.\n\n*   **Global Cooperation:** The fight against money laundering is a global effort, with countries cooperating through information sharing, joint investigations, and mutual legal assistance. International organizations like the FATF play a crucial role in setting standards, monitoring compliance, and promoting best practices in anti-money laundering (AML) efforts.\n\n*   **Economic and Social Harm:** Money laundering has detrimental consequences for societies and economies. It enables criminal activity, undermines financial integrity, distorts markets, and can even pose a threat to national security. Because of this, there is widespread agreement that it must be combatted.\n\n*   **Absence of Legal Arguments for Legitimacy:** There are no credible or legitimate legal arguments that support the permissibility of money laundering. It is universally recognized as an attempt to hide the proceeds of crime and is therefore unlawful.\n\nIn conclusion, the illegality of money laundering is firmly established in international law, national legislation, and global policy. There is no legitimate debate or disagreement on this point.",
